ary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for an officer of a court of justice, from Middle English <i>bailli</i>, <i>baillif</i> ‘manager, administrator’ (Old French <i>bailli(s)</i>, <i>baillif</i>). The term could denote the king's officer in a county, hundred, town, castle, or forest, or an elected town officer, a magistrate, an officer of a court, serving warrants and enforcing judgments. In Middle English, a bailiff often denoted the agent of a lord in managing a manor, collecting rents, etc., but in the early modern period the term gradually because specialized as denoting an officer of justice under a sheriff, who executes writs and processes, distraints, and arrests. Compare the variant   Bayliff  ,   Bayliss   and also   Bailey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bayliff","meanings":["English: variant of   Bailiff  . See also   Bayliss  ."]},{"name":"Bayliss","meanings":["English: variant of   Bailiff  , with excrescent <i>-s</i>, an occupational name for an officer of a court of justice, whose duties included serving writs, distraining goods, and (formerly) arresting people. In England it was formerly a status name for the chief officer of a hundred (administrative subdivision of a county). The derivation is from Middle English, Old French <i>bailis</i>, from Late Latin <i>baiulivus</i> (adjective), ‘pertaining to an attendant or porter’ (see   Bailey  ).","History: Thomas Baylies, a prominent Quaker, came to Boston from London in 1737."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Roger Bailiffe was born in 1329, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs Roger Bailiffe. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1329–":"1329–Surnud","1333–Female":"1333–Surnud","1345–1392":"1345–1392","1329–Male":"1329–Surnud","1345":"1345","1333":"1333","1392":"1392","1329":"1329","Barsley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Barnsley, Yorkshire, England":"Barnsley, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1329–":"1329–Kuollut","1333–Female":"1333–Kuollut","1345–1392":"1345–1392","1329–Male":"1329–Kuollut","1345":"1345","1333":"1333","1392":"1392","1329":"1329","Barsley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Barnsley, Yorkshire, England":"Barnsley, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1329–":"1329–Décédé","1333–Female":"1333–Décédée","1345–1392":"1345–1392","1329–Male":"1329–Décédé","1345":"1345","1333":"1333","1392":"1392","1329":"1329","Barsley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Barnsley, Yorkshire, England":"Barnsley, Everwyck, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Roger Bailiffe est né en 1329, à Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Mrs Roger Bailiffe. Il est décédé dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"1329–":"1329–Verstorben","1333–Female":"1333–Verstorben","1345–1392":"1345–1392","1329–Male":"1329–Verstorben","1345":"1345","1333":"1333","1392":"1392","1329":"1329","Barsley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Yorkshire, England, Uni